Linux Networking Commands Diagram (Week 2)
[Your WSL Ubuntu System]
          |
          |--- ping ---â–¶ [Remote Server / Website]
          |        (Check if online, measure latency)
          |
          |--- curl -I ---â–¶ [Remote Server / Website]
          |        (Check HTTP headers, server response)
          |
          |--- netstat ---â–¶ [Local Ports & Connections]
          |        (Which processes are listening / connected)
          |
          |--- ifconfig ---â–¶ [Local Network Interfaces]
          |        (Check IP addresses, status, network config)
          |
          |--- Bash Script (uptime.sh) ---â–¶ Combines ping + logging
          |        (Automates monitoring website and logs results)
________________________________________
Step-by-Step Explanation
1.	Ping
o	Your system â†’ sends â€œecho requestsâ€ â†’ remote server â†’ responds â†’ you see latency
o	Used to check if a server is reachable
2.	Curl -I
o	Your system â†’ sends HTTP request headers â†’ remote server responds â†’ you see status codes
o	Used to check if a website is running and returning 200 OK
3.	Netstat
o	Your system â†’ lists all open network ports and their processes
o	Useful to see what is running locally (like nginx, Docker containers)
4.	Ifconfig
o	Your system â†’ shows network interfaces (eth0, wlan0, etc.)
o	Displays IP address, MAC address, and interface status
5.	Bash Script (uptime.sh)
o	Combines ping + logic to check server availability
o	Logs the result into a file for later reference
o	Can be automated to run every minute/hour
________________________________________
Example Workflow for Monitoring a Website
1.	Use ping to check if Google is online. âœ…
2.	If online, echo timestamp + status â†’ append to status.log
3.	If not online, echo timestamp + â€œDownâ€ â†’ append to status.log
4.	Optionally check netstat to see if any services (like nginx) are running
5.	Use ifconfig if you need your local IP for testing connections
